  monumentInformation:
    monumentInformation:
    - title: Who Built It
      details:
      - "The Nabataeans \u2013 an ancient Arabian civilization \u2013 were responsible
        for building Petra, carving it into rose-red cliffs between the 4th century
        BCE and 2nd century CE."
      - "King Aretas IV (9 BCE\u201340 CE), a Nabataean king, played a significant
        role in the expansion and development of Petra into a thriving trade hub."
    - title: Where It Is Located
      details:
      - Petra is located in southern Jordan, between the Red Sea and the Dead Sea,
        near the modern town of Wadi Musa.
      - The city is nestled in a rugged, desert canyon and can be accessed via the
        Siq, a narrow, winding gorge approximately 1.2 kilometers long.
    - title: When It Was Built
      details:
      - The earliest structures in Petra were built around the 4th century BCE when
        the Nabataeans settled in the area.
      - The city reached its architectural peak between the 1st century BCE and 2nd
        century CE, with key monuments such as the Treasury (Al-Khazneh) and the
        Monastery (Ad-Deir).
    - title: Who Is It Protected By
      details:
      - UNESCO declared Petra a World Heritage Site in 1985 for its unique architecture
        and historical importance.
      - The site is managed and protected by the Petra Development and Tourism Region
        Authority (PDTRA) and the Department of Antiquities of Jordan.
    - title: Why It Was Built
      details:
      - Petra was established as the capital of the Nabataean Kingdom, serving as
        a strategic center for trade routes connecting Arabia, Egypt, and the Mediterranean.
      - The structures, including tombs and temples, symbolized the Nabataean's ingenuity
        in water management and architecture, demonstrating their prosperity and
        cultural sophistication.
